Writting React Testing Library + Vitest like pro

## Quick Setup (so our examples just work)

```
// vitest.config.ts
import { defineConfig } from 'vitest/config';

export default defineConfig({
  test: {
    environment: 'jsdom',
    setupFiles: ['./vitest.setup.ts'],
    css: false,
  },
});
```

```
// vitest.setup.ts
import '@testing-library/jest-dom/vitest'; // RTL matchers in Vitest
```

## 1) Testing Implementation Details Instead of Behavior

**Symptom:** you assert on internal state, class names, or component internals. Refactors break tests that should’ve been stable.

**DON’T**

```
// ❌ Asserting on class names or internal state
expect(button.classList.contains('btn--primary')).toBe(true);
```

**DO**

```
// ✅ Assert what the user can perceive
import { render, screen } from '@testing-library/react';
import user from '@testing-library/user-event';
import { SaveForm } from './SaveForm';

test('saves after clicking the Save button', async () => {
  render(<SaveForm />);
  await user.click(screen.getByRole('button', { name: /save/i }));
  expect(await screen.findByText(/saved!/i)).toBeVisible();
});
```

**Rule of thumb:** If a real user can’t see/trigger it, you probably shouldn’t assert it.

## 2) Using `getBy*` When the UI Updates Asynchronously

**Symptom:** random failures, “Unable to find element” even though the app works.

**DON’T**

```
// ❌ getBy* fails if the element appears after a fetch or timeout
expect(screen.getByText(/welcome/i)).toBeVisible();
```

**DO**

```
// ✅ findBy* waits for the element to show up (default 1s timeout)
expect(await screen.findByText(/welcome/i)).toBeVisible();
```

**When to use what**

- `getBy*`: element **must be there now**, otherwise throw.
- `queryBy*`: element **should not** be there.
- `findBy*`: element **will appear later** (async)

## 3) Wrangling `waitFor` Wrong

**Symptom:** you wrap everything in `waitFor` or nest waits and `findBy*`. Tests become slow and flaky.

**DON’T**

```
// ❌ Nesting waits and using findBy inside waitFor is redundant
await waitFor(async () => {
  expect(await screen.findByText('Done')).toBeInTheDocument();
});
```

**DO**

```
// ✅ Use findBy*, or use waitFor with sync expectations
expect(await screen.findByText('Done')).toBeInTheDocument();

// or, if you truly need to poll a sync assertion:
await waitFor(() => {
  expect(screen.getByRole('button', { name: /save/i })).toBeEnabled();
});
```

## 4) Firing Events Like a Robot (`fireEvent`) Instead of a Human (`userEvent`)

**Symptom:** tests pass but miss real-world issues like focus, typing delays, or input composition.

**DON’T**

```
import { fireEvent } from '@testing-library/react';
// ❌ unrealistically sets value without user behavior
fireEvent.change(input, { target: { value: 'abc' }});
```

**DO**

```
import user from '@testing-library/user-event';
// ✅ simulates actual typing and focus
await user.type(input, 'abc');
```

Use `userEvent` by default. Keep `fireEvent` for rare low-level cases.

## 5) Role/Text Queries Done Wrong (a11y ignored)

**Symptom:** you scatter `getByTestId` everywhere. You miss accessibility issues and make tests brittle.

**DON’T**

```
// ❌ testids everywhere
screen.getByTestId('submit-btn');
```

**DO**

```
// ✅ Prefer role + accessible name
screen.getByRole('button', { name: /submit/i });
screen.getByLabelText(/email/i);
screen.getByPlaceholderText(/search/i);
```

Test like a user with assistive tech. It’s more robust and catches a11y regressions for free.

## 6) Forgetting Providers (Router/Theme/QueryClient/etc.)

**Symptom:** “useNavigate must be used within a Router”, “No QueryClient set”, theme tokens undefined.

**DON’T**

```
// ❌ Rendering component without required providers
render(<ProfilePage />);
```

**DO**

```
// ✅ Centralized test utils
import { render as rtlRender } from '@testing-library/react';
import { BrowserRouter } from 'react-router-dom';
import { QueryClient, QueryClientProvider } from '@tanstack/react-query';

const render = (ui: React.ReactElement) => {
  const client = new QueryClient();
  return rtlRender(
    <BrowserRouter>
      <QueryClientProvider client={client}>{ui}</QueryClientProvider>
    </BrowserRouter>
  );
};

test('loads profile', async () => {
  render(<ProfilePage />);
  expect(await screen.findByText(/hello, sam/i)).toBeVisible();
});
```

Create a `test-utils.tsx` and **always** use it.

## 7) Mocking Network the Hard Way (or the Wrong Way)

**Symptom:** brittle `fetch` mocks, tests coupled to endpoints, impossible error-path testing.

**DON’T**

```
// ❌ ad-hoc fetch spies everywhere
vi.spyOn(global, 'fetch').mockResolvedValue(/* ... */);
```

**DO (MSW recommended)**

```
// ✅ /src/mocks/handlers.ts
import { http, HttpResponse } from 'msw';

export const handlers = [\
  http.get('/api/user', () => HttpResponse.json({ name: 'Sam' })),\
];
```

```
// vitest.setup.ts
import { setupServer } from 'msw/node';
import { handlers } from './src/mocks/handlers';

const server = setupServer(...handlers);

beforeAll(() => server.listen());
afterEach(() => server.resetHandlers());
afterAll(() => server.close());
```

MSW gives you declarative, realistic network tests (and easy error cases).

## 8) Ignoring Fake Timers (and Then Wrestling With Them)

**Symptom:** components using `setTimeout`/debounce lead to hanging tests.

**DON’T**

```
// ❌ Forget timers; test never advances
await user.type(input, 'hello');
// ...no progress
```

**DO**

```
// ✅ Advance time when using debounced logic
vi.useFakeTimers();
await user.type(input, 'hello');
vi.advanceTimersByTime(300); // debounce window
expect(await screen.findByText(/suggestions/i)).toBeVisible();
vi.useRealTimers();
```

Keep timers symmetrical: `useFakeTimers()` → `useRealTimers()`.

## 9) `act(...)` Warnings From Async Work

**Symptom:** “Warning: An update to X inside a test was not wrapped in act(…)”.

**DON’T**

```
// ❌ Forgetting to await async user interactions
user.click(screen.getByRole('button', { name: /load/i }));
// test exits before update commits
```

**DO**

```
// ✅ Always await userEvent, use findBy* for async UI
await user.click(screen.getByRole('button', { name: /load/i }));
expect(await screen.findByText(/loaded/i)).toBeVisible();
```

If you still see warnings, something in your component is updating state outside your awaited flow — trace it.

## 10) Snapshot Testing Everything

**Symptom:** enormous `.snap` files that fail on harmless changes.

