**DON’T**

```
// ❌ mass snapshots
expect(container).toMatchSnapshot();
```

**DO**

```
// ✅ Assert concrete, user-visible behavior
expect(screen.getByRole('heading', { name: /inbox/i })).toBeVisible();
expect(screen.getAllByRole('listitem')).toHaveLength(5);
expect(screen.getByRole('button', { name: /delete/i })).toBeDisabled()
```

Use snapshots sparingly (e.g., tiny, stable serializable utilities — not UI).

## 11) Mixing ESM Mocks Wrong in Vitest

**Symptom:** your default export mock isn’t used; you get “undefined is not a function”.

**DON’T**

```
// ❌ Missing default in ESM mock
vi.mock('./api', () => ({ fetchUser: vi.fn() }));
```

**DO**

```
// ✅ Provide default for ESM default imports
vi.mock('./api', () => ({
  default: { fetchUser: vi.fn().mockResolvedValue({ name: 'Sam' }) },
  fetchUser: vi.fn(), // if also named export
}));
```

Or import consistently (default vs named). Don’t mix both randomly.

## 12) Not Cleaning Up After Each Test

RTL auto-cleans DOM, but your **mocks, timers, QueryClient, localStorage** may leak.

**DON’T**

```
// ❌ no resets → state bleeds across tests
```

**DO**

```
afterEach(() => {
  vi.clearAllMocks();
  vi.useRealTimers();
  window.localStorage.clear();
});
```

If you spin up clients (e.g., React Query), create new instances per test.

## 13) Asserting Removal with `getBy*` Instead of `queryBy*`

**Symptom:** tests crash when the element is expected to be gone.

**DON’T**

```
// ❌ getBy throws if not found
expect(screen.getByText(/loading/i)).not.toBeInTheDocument();
```

**DO**

```
// ✅ queryBy returns null if not found
await waitFor(() => {
  expect(screen.queryByText(/loading/i)).not.toBeInTheDocument();
});
```

## 14) Testing Hooks With the Wrong Tooling

As of modern RTL, `renderHook` is exposed from `@testing-library/react`.

**DON’T**

```
// ❌ Deprecated packages / custom wrappers you don’t need
```

**DO**

```
import { renderHook, act } from '@testing-library/react';

function useCounter() {
  const [n, set] = React.useState(0);
  return { n, inc: () => set((x) => x + 1) };
}

test('useCounter increments', () => {
  const { result } = renderHook(() => useCounter());
  act(() => result.current.inc());
  expect(result.current.n).toBe(1);
});
```

If your hook depends on providers, wrap with your `test-utils` provider tree.

## 15) Treating JSDOM Like a Real Browser

JSDOM ≠ Chrome. Layout APIs, canvas, and some browser features don’t exist.

**DON’T**

```
// ❌ Expecting clientHeight or canvas drawing to be real
expect(el.clientHeight).toBeGreaterThan(0);
```

**DO**

- Abstract layout/canvas logic into testable pure functions.
- For web APIs, **mock** them, or use **Playwright**/ **Cypress** for true browser tests.

## 16) Overusing `screen.debug()` Instead of Writing Better Queries

If your `getByRole` fails, it’s often because the component isn’t accessible or the name is wrong.

**Suggestion:** Use `logRoles(container)` to see what’s actually queryable.

```
import { render, screen, logRoles } from '@testing-library/react';

const { container } = render(<MyComponent />);
logRoles(container);
```

Fix your component’s semantics; your tests will get simpler.

## 17) Not Configuring Type-Safe `userEvent`

Always `await` user actions; TypeScript will help you catch missing `await`s if you enable `no-floating-promises`.

**DO**

```
await user.click(...);
await user.type(...);
await user.selectOptions(...);
```

## 18) Ignoring Useful Matchers

If you’re still writing `expect(el.getAttribute('disabled')).not.toBeNull()`, stop.

**DO** (from `@testing-library/jest-dom/vitest`)

```
expect(button).toBeDisabled();
expect(link).toHaveAttribute('href', '/home');
expect(img).toHaveAccessibleName('User avatar');
expect(input).toHaveValue('abc');
expect(el).toHaveTextContent(/saved/i);
```

## Full Example: Putting It All Together

```
// LoginForm.tsx
import * as React from 'react';

export function LoginForm({ onLogin }: { onLogin: (u: string, p: string) => Promise<void> }) {
  const [status, setStatus] = React.useState<'idle'|'loading'|'done'|'error'>('idle');

  async function handleSubmit(e: React.FormEvent) {
    e.preventDefault();
    setStatus('loading');
    const form = e.currentTarget as HTMLFormElement;
    const u = (form.elements.namedItem('email') as HTMLInputElement).value;
    const p = (form.elements.namedItem('password') as HTMLInputElement).value;

    try {
      await onLogin(u, p);
      setStatus('done');
    } catch {
      setStatus('error');
    }
  }

  return (
    <form aria-label="login" onSubmit={handleSubmit}>
      <label>
        Email
        <input name="email" type="email" />
      </label>
      <label>
        Password
        <input name="password" type="password" />
      </label>
      <button type="submit" disabled={status === 'loading'}>Sign in</button>
      {status === 'loading' && <div role="status">Loading…</div>}
      {status === 'done' && <p>Welcome back!</p>}
      {status === 'error' && <p role="alert">Invalid credentials</p>}
    </form>
  );
}
```

```
// LoginForm.test.tsx
import { render, screen } from '@testing-library/react';
import user from '@testing-library/user-event';
import { vi } from 'vitest';
import { LoginForm } from './LoginForm';

test('happy path', async () => {
  const onLogin = vi.fn().mockResolvedValue(undefined);
  render(<LoginForm onLogin={onLogin} />);
  await user.type(screen.getByLabelText(/email/i), 'sam@example.com');
  await user.type(screen.getByLabelText(/password/i), 'secret');
  await user.click(screen.getByRole('button', { name: /sign in/i }));
  expect(await screen.findByText(/welcome back/i)).toBeVisible();
  expect(onLogin).toHaveBeenCalledWith('sam@example.com', 'secret');
  expect(screen.queryByRole('status')).not.toBeInTheDocument();
});

test('error path', async () => {
  const onLogin = vi.fn().mockRejectedValue(new Error('nope'));
  render(<LoginForm onLogin={onLogin} />);
  await user.click(screen.getByRole('button', { name: /sign in/i }));
  expect(await screen.findByRole('alert')).toHaveTextContent(/invalid/i);
});
```

This suite:

- Uses **role/label queries**
- Uses **userEvent**
- Uses **findBy**\\* for async UI
- Avoids implementation details and snapshots

## Checklist You Can Paste Into Your PR

- Queries use **role/label/placeholder** (not testids by default).
- Asynchronous UI uses `findBy*` or `waitFor` correctly.
- `userEvent` is used for interactions (and always `await` **ed**).
- Providers wrapped via shared `render` util.
- Network mocked via **MSW** (not ad-hoc fetch spies).
- No snapshots for components — assert behavior, not markup.
- Fake timers used + restored when needed.
- No `act(...)` warnings.
- No leaking mocks/state between tests.
- Hook tests use `renderHook` (with providers if needed).

## Alternatives & When to Use Them

- **Playwright/Cypress**: full browser + network; use for **flows** and **layout-sensitive** checks.
- **Storybook + @storybook/testing-library**: component states + interaction tests close to design system.
- **Vitest + happy-dom**: faster than jsdom in some cases, but less spec-accurate; use thoughtfully.

## Final Word

Most flaky RTL tests come from **pretending to be the DOM** instead of **acting like a user**. Use semantic queries, await async UI, and mock networks smartly. Your tests will become **shorter, faster, and harder to break**.

